		{"id":"bd098e61eded86b5","type":"text","text":"### Tips\n1. Use one bold focal image that captures your novel’s core emotion.\n2. Limit colors to a strong two‑ or three‑tone palette.\n3. Choose typography that reflects the book’s mood and era.\n4. Study covers in your genre and deliberately break one rule.\n5. Create a symbolic element that hints at the story without spoiling it.\n### Size & Trim\n1. Pick a standard trim (most common: 5×8, 5.25×8, 6×9) to avoid printing issues.\n2. Keep spine width accurate to your final page count and paper type.\n3. Leave safe margins: at least 0.125” bleed and 0.25” interior safety.\n4. Ensure text stays clear of edges, especially on the spine.\n5. Export final art in CMYK at 300 DPI for clean print results.","x":-3360,"y":1698,"width":540,"height":916,"color":"2"}
